'''Felipe Muñoz Kapamas''' (born February 3, 1951)<ref>[https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mu/felipe-munoz-1.html Felipe Muñoz] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081224082014/http://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mu/felipe-munoz-1.html |date=2008-12-24 }}. sports-reference.com.</ref> is a retired [[breaststroke]] swimmer from [[Mexico]]. He competed at the [[Mexico at the 1968 Summer Olympics|1968]] and [[Mexico at the 1972 Summer Olympics|1972 Summer Olympics]] and won a gold medal in the 200 m event in 1968. Since 2008, he is the President of the Mexican Olympic Committee.<ref>{{es icon}} [http://www.com.org.mx/f/ Comité Olímpico Mexicano website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071017015551/http://www.com.org.mx/f/ |date=2007-10-17 }} (subpage ''Estructura Orgánica'') listing Muñoz as the current president of the Mexican Olympic Committee. Retrieved 2010-07-08.</ref> Since 2012 he serves as Deputy of the [[LXII Legislature of the Mexican Congress]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Chamber of Deputies|url=http://sitl.diputados.gob.mx/LXII_leg/curricula.php?dipt=436|publisher=Chamber of Deputies|accessdate=14 October 2014}}</ref>

Muñoz is of [[Greece|Greek]] descent on his mother's side.<ref>{{es icon}} [http://www.elsiglodetorreon.com.mx/noticia/105872.le-salen-parientes-griegos-a-felipe-tibio-mun.html Le salen parientes griegos a Felipe 'Tibio' Muñoz Kapamas], published by ''El Siglo de Torreón'' on 2004-08-24; retrieved 2010-07-08.</ref>

His nickname is "el tibio", which means "lukewarm" in Spanish. It was coined because Felipe's father was from [[Aguascalientes]], meaning "hot waters", and his mother was from the town of [[Río Frío de Juárez|Río Frío]], [[Mexico State]], meaning "cold river".  He had the habit of refusing to swim in an unheated pool.

