{{Infobox venue | name = Färjestads ishall | nickname = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | fullname = | former names = | logo_image = | logo_caption = | image = | image_size = | image_alt = | caption = | pushpin_map = | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | address = | location = [[Karlstad]], [[Sweden]] | coordinates = | type = [[ice hockey rink|indoor ice hockey rink]] | genre = | broke_ground = | built = | opened = {{start date|November 1967|df=y}} | renovated = | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | operator = | surface = | scoreboard = | production = | cost = | architect = | builder = | project_manager = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | main_contractors = | seating_type = | capacity = | suites = | record_attendance = | dimensions = | field_shape = | acreage = | volume = | tenants = | embedded = | website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} --> | publictransit = }} '''Färjestads Ishall''' was an [[arena]] in [[Karlstad Municipality|Karlstad]], [[Sweden]]. It was the home arena for the [[ice hockey]] team [[Färjestad BK|Färjestads BK]]. It opened in November 1967<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.farjestadbk.se/artikel/ohycains3-23h01/fbk-80-ar-fran-tjarn-till-arena|title=FBK 80 år: Från tjärn till Arena|publisher=Färjestads BK|language=Swedish|date=2012|accessdate=19 March 2018}}</ref> and held initially 8,000 people during sport events, but the capacity was later reduced to 4,700 when seating became common standard. [[Löfbergs Arena|Löfbergs Lila Arena]] replaced it as the home of Färjestad.
